an life that encompasses history, archaeology, geography, and the love of place that suffuses us when we finally find home. Firmly in a storied tradition of English nature writing that stretches from Gilbert White to Helen MacDonald, Rising Ground reveals the ways that places and peoples have interacted over time, from standing stones to footpaths, ancient habitations to modern highways. What does it mean to truly live in a place, and what does it take to understand, and honor, those who lived and died there long before we arrived? Like the best travel and nature writing, Rising Ground is written with the pace of a contemplative walk, and is rich with insight and a powerful sense of the long skein of years that links us to our ancestors. Marsden’s close, loving look at the small patch of earth around him is sure to help you see your own place—and your own home—anew.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHistoric sites - England - Cornwall (County). 0aHistoric siteszEnglandzCornwall (County) 0aHistoric siteszEnglandzCornwall (County). 7aTravel / General.2bisacsh  atravel writing, travelogue, farmhouse, cornwall, country, landscape, lands end, walking, place, nature, wilderness, history, geography, archaeology, space, belonging, reflection, introspection, meditation, nonfiction, memoir, biography, autobiography, standing stones, footpaths, antiquities, glastonbury, tintagel, garrow tor, bodmin moor, ardevora, mendip, porthleven, tolverne, ruan creek, tregony, fal, hensbarrow, scilly, lethowsow, nanjizal, zennor, madron, morrab.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311071098440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226366128423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226366128/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicag